[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The **categorical abstract machine** (**CAM**) is a model of computation for programs that preserves the abilities of applicative, functional, or compositional style.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] It is based on the techniques of applicative computing.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The notion of the categorical abstract machine arose in the mid-1980s.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] It took its place in computer science as a kind of theory of computation for programmers, represented by Cartesian closed category and embedded into the combinatory logic.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] CAM is a transparent and sound mathematical representation for the languages of functional programming.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The machine code can be optimized using the equational form of a theory of computation.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] Using CAM, the various mechanisms of computation such as recursion or lazy evaluation can be emulated as well as parameter passing, such as call by name, call by value, and so on.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] In theory, CAM preserves all the advantages of object approach towards programming or computing.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The main current implementation is OCaml, which added class inheritance and dynamic method dispatch to Caml the Categorical Abstract Machine Language.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] Both are variants of MetaLanguage ML, and all three languages implement type inference.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] One of the implementation approaches to functional languages is given by the machinery based on supercombinators, or an SK-machine, by D.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The notion of CAM gives an alternative approach.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The structure of CAM consists of syntactic, semantic, and computational constituents.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] Syntax is based on de Bruijn’s notation, which overcomes the difficulties of using bound variables.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] The evaluations are similar to those of P.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] With this coverage, CAM gives a sound ground for syntax, semantics, and theory of computation.
[src:graph-reduction/categorical-abstract-machine] This comprehension arises as being influenced by the functional style of programming.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In combinatory logic for computer science, a **fixed-point combinator** (or **fixpoint combinator**) is a higher-order function (i.e., a function that takes a function as argument) that returns some *fixed point* (a value that is mapped to itself) of its argument function, if one exists.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Fixed-point combinators can be defined in the lambda calculus and in functional programming languages, and provide a means to allow for recursive definitions.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Applied to a non-constant function of one variable that treats its argument as a piece of data (such as e.g. the sine function), the Y combinator usually does not terminate.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The resulting function behaves like a *while* or a *for* loop.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Used in this way, the Y combinator implements general recursion.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The lambda calculus does not have global names, for a function to refer to itself by name inside its own definition, as is possible in many programming languages.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] But it has local names, i.e. parameters in lambda abstractions.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] An abstraction term can receive another term as an argument, and refer to that argument by the parameter name inside the function's body.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Y combinator may also be used in implementing Curry's paradox.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The heart of Curry's paradox is that untyped lambda calculus is unsound as a deductive system, and the Y combinator demonstrates this by allowing an anonymous expression to represent zero, or even many values.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This is inconsistent in mathematical logic.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In the classical untyped lambda calculus, every function has a fixed point.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The lambda term $g\ (\mathrm {Y} \ g)$ may not, in general, β-reduce to the term $\mathrm {Y} \ g$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] However, both terms β-reduce to the same term, as shown.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Y is only needed when function names are absent.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This works because R uses lazy evaluation.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Languages that use strict evaluation, such as Python, C++, and other strict programming languages, can often express Y; however, any implementation is useless in practice since it loops indefinitely until terminating via a stack overflow.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Y combinator is an implementation of a fixed-point combinator in lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Fixed-point combinators may also be easily defined in other functional and imperative languages.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The implementation in lambda calculus is more difficult due to limitations in lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Fixed-point combinators may be applied to a range of different functions, but normally will not terminate unless there is an extra parameter.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] When the function to be fixed refers to its parameter, another call to the function is invoked, so the calculation never gets started.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Instead, the extra parameter is used to trigger the start of the calculation.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The type of the fixed point is the return type of the function being fixed.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This may be a real or a function or any other type.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In the untyped lambda calculus, the function to apply the fixed-point combinator to may be expressed using an encoding, like Church encoding.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In this case particular lambda terms (which define functions) are considered as values.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] "Running" (beta reducing) the fixed-point combinator on the encoding gives a lambda term for the result, which may then be interpreted as fixed-point value.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Alternately, a function may be considered as a lambda term defined purely in lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] These different approaches affect how a mathematician and a programmer may regard a fixed-point combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A mathematician may see the Y combinator applied to a function as being an expression satisfying the fixed-point equation, and therefore a solution.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In contrast, a person only wanting to apply a fixed-point combinator to some general programming task may see it only as a means of implementing recursion.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Many functions do not have any fixed points, for instance $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f(n)=n+1$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Using Church encoding, natural numbers can be represented in lambda calculus, and this function *f* can be defined in lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] However, its domain will now contain *all* lambda expressions, not just those representing natural numbers.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Y combinator, applied to *f*, will yield a fixed-point for *f*, but this fixed-point won't represent a natural number.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] If trying to compute Y *f* in an actual programming language, an infinite loop will occur.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The fixed-point combinator may be defined in mathematics and then implemented in other languages.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] General mathematics defines a function based on its extensional properties.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] That is, two functions are equal if they perform the same mapping.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Lambda calculus and programming languages regard function identity as an intensional property.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A function's identity is based on its implementation.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A lambda calculus function (or term) is an implementation of a mathematical function.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In the lambda calculus there are a number of combinators (implementations) that satisfy the mathematical definition of a fixed-point combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Combinatory logic is a higher-order functions theory.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A combinator is a *closed* lambda expression, meaning that it has no free variables.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The combinators may be combined to direct values to their correct places in the expression without ever naming them as variables.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Fixed-point combinators can be used to implement recursive definition of functions.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] However, they are rarely used in practical programming.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Strongly normalizing type systems such as the simply typed lambda calculus disallow non-termination and hence fixed-point combinators often cannot be assigned a type or require complex type system features.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Furthermore, fixed-point combinators are often inefficient compared to other strategies for implementing recursion, as they require more function reductions and construct and take apart a tuple for each group of mutually recursive definitions.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The factorial function provides a good example of how a fixed-point combinator may be used to define recursive functions.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This poses a problem, though, as $\operatorname {fact}$ inside the definition of $\operatorname {fact}$ cannot possibly signify the inclusion of the definition as a whole inside itself.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Instead, as it normally goes almost unnoticed, it is the reference to the definition by its *name*.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This presupposes the existence of a global registry of names, so called "environment".
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] And the lambda calculus lacks this entirely.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Still, name references do exist in lambda calculus – local names, names of parameters of a given function.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Splitting off a separate copy of $\operatorname {f}$ and passing it as an argument to itself makes it available to itself to be called, as and if needed, inside itself.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In such a call it must again be passed along as an argument so it will be available to the next invocation, and so on, as the chain of invocations progresses.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The definition of $\operatorname {f}$ is *open recursive*, and calling $\operatorname {f}$ with itself as an argument at the top closes the circle.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Implementing this in lambda calculus is now trivial, and directly leads to the definition of the Y combinator, one instance of a fixed-point combinator, such that $\operatorname {fix} f=f\,(\operatorname {fix} f)$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In untyped lambda calculus fixed-point combinators are not especially rare.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In fact there are infinitely many of them.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In 2005 Mayer Goldberg showed that the set of fixed-point combinators of untyped lambda calculus is recursively enumerable.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Additional combinators (B, C, K, W system) allow for much shorter encodings.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] although note that it is not in normal form, which is longer.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Its advantage over ${\mathsf {Y}}$ is that $\Theta \ f$ beta-reduces to $f\ (\Theta f)$ , whereas ${\mathsf {Y}}\ f$ and $f\ ({\mathsf {Y}}f)$ only beta-reduce to a common term.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The analog for mutual recursion is a *polyvariadic fix-point combinator*, which may be denoted Y*.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In a strict programming language the Y combinator will expand until stack overflow, or never halt in case of tail call optimization.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Z combinator will work in strict languages (also called eager languages, where applicative evaluation order is applied).
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Terms that have the same Böhm tree as a fixed-point combinator, i.e., have the same infinite extension $\lambda x.x(x(x\cdots ))$ , are called *non-standard fixed-point combinators*.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Any fixed-point combinator is also a non-standard one, but not all non-standard fixed-point combinators are fixed-point combinators because some of them fail to satisfy the fixed-point equation that defines the "standard" ones.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] where ${\mathsf {N}}_{i}$ are modifications of ${\mathsf {N}}$ created on the fly which add i instances of x at once into the chain while being replaced with ${\mathsf {N}}_{i+1}$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The set of non-standard fixed-point combinators is not recursively enumerable.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Y combinator is a particular implementation of a fixed-point combinator in lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Its structure is determined by the limitations of lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] It is not necessary or helpful to use this structure in implementing the fixed-point combinator in other languages.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Simple examples of fixed-point combinators implemented in some programming paradigms are given below.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In a language that supports lazy evaluation, as in Haskell, it is possible to define a fixed-point combinator using the defining equation of the fixed-point combinator which is conventionally named `fix`.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Since Haskell has lazy data types, this combinator can also be used to define fixed points of data constructors (and not only to implement recursive functions).
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The definition is given here, followed by some usage examples.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This may be resolved by defining fix with an extra parameter.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] This example is a slightly interpretive implementation of a fixed-point combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A class is used to contain the `fix()` function, called `FixedPointCombinator`.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The function to be fixed is contained in a class that inherits from fixer.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The `fix()` function accesses the function to be fixed using a concept to call `apply()`.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] As for the strict functional definition, `fix()` is explicitly given an extra parameter `x`, which means that lazy evaluation is not needed.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] That is, if the type of $\mathrm {fix} \ f$ fulfilling the equation $\mathrm {fix} \ f\ =\ f\ (\mathrm {fix} \ f)$ is a —the most general type—then the type of f is $a\to a$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] So then, $\mathrm {fix}$ takes a function that maps a to a and uses it to return a value of type a .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In the simply typed lambda calculus extended with recursive data types, fixed-point operators can be written, but the type of a "useful" fixed-point operator (one whose application always returns) may be restricted.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] No fixed-point combinator can in fact be typed; in those systems, any support for recursion must be explicitly added to the language.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Thus $R\ a:=R\ a\to a$ is recognized as a recursive type.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A datum (value) of the type $R\ a$ is created by simply tagging a value that is a function that has the type $R\ a\to a$ , by the data constructor tag for the type $R\ a$ .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] But the expression `app x x` above *is* typeable.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Some languages allow for explicitly marking general types as being recursive even without naming them.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Doing that also allows for defining the $\operatorname {Y}$ combinator in such languages.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] A function for which *every* input is a fixed point is called an identity function.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In contrast to universal quantification over all x , a fixed-point combinator constructs *one* value that is a fixed point of f .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The remarkable property of a fixed-point combinator is that it constructs a fixed point for an *arbitrary given* function f .
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Other functions have the special property that, after being applied once, further applications don't have any effect.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Such functions are called idempotent (see also Projection (mathematics)).
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] An example of such a function is the function that returns 0 for all even integers, and 1 for all odd integers.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In lambda calculus, from a computational point of view, applying a fixed-point combinator to an identity function or an idempotent function typically results in non-terminating computation.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] where the resulting term can only reduce to itself and represents an infinite loop.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] Fixed-point combinators do not necessarily exist in more restrictive models of computation.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] For instance, they do not exist in simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] The Y combinator allows recursion to be defined as a set of rewrite rules, without requiring native recursion support in the language.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In programming languages that support anonymous functions, fixed-point combinators allow the definition and use of anonymous recursive functions, i.e., without having to bind such functions to identifiers.
[src:graph-reduction/fixed-point-combinator] In this setting, the use of fixed-point combinators is sometimes called *anonymous recursion*.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] In computer science, **graph reduction** implements an efficient version of non-strict evaluation, an evaluation strategy where the arguments to a function are not immediately evaluated.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] This form of non-strict evaluation is also known as lazy evaluation and used in functional programming languages.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] The technique was first developed by Chris Wadsworth in 1971.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] The above reduction sequence employs a strategy known as outermost tree reduction.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] Notice that the reduction order is made explicit by the addition of parentheses.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] This expression could also have been simply evaluated right to left, because addition is an associative operation.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] This is where the term tree reduction comes from.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] When represented as a tree, we can think of innermost reduction as working from the bottom up, while outermost works from the top down.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] As for trees, outermost and innermost reduction also applies to graphs.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] Notice that evaluation now only requires four steps.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] Outermost graph reduction is referred to as lazy evaluation and innermost graph reduction is referred to as eager evaluation.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] The concept of a graph reduction that allows evaluated values to be shared was first developed by Chris Wadsworth in his 1971 Ph.D. dissertation.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] This dissertation was cited by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] Morris Jr. in 1976 paper, “A lazy evaluator” that introduced the notion of lazy evaluation.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] In 1976 David Turner incorporated lazy evaluation into SASL using combinators.
[src:graph-reduction/graph-reduction] SASL was an early functional programming language first developed by Turner in 1972.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] In theoretical computer science, the **Krivine machine** is an *abstract machine*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] As an abstract machine, it shares features with Turing machines and the SECD machine.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The Krivine machine explains how to compute a recursive function.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] More specifically it aims to define rigorously head normal form reduction of a lambda term using call-by-name reduction.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] Thanks to its formalism, it tells in details how a kind of reduction works and sets the theoretical foundation of the operational semantics of functional programming languages.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] On the other hand, Krivine machine implements call-by-name because it evaluates the body of a β-redex before it applies the body to its parameter.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] In other words, in an expression (*λ* *x*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] In functional programming, this would mean that in order to evaluate a function applied to a parameter, it evaluates first the function before applying it to the parameter.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The Krivine machine was designed by the French logician Jean-Louis Krivine at the beginning of the 1980s.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The Krivine machine is based on two concepts related to lambda calculus, namely head reduction and call by name.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] A redex (one says also β-redex) is a term of the lambda calculus of the form (*λ* *x*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] A *head normal form* is a term of the lambda calculus which is not a head redex.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] A *head reduction* is a (non empty) sequence of contractions of a term which contracts head redexes.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] A head reduction of a term *t* (which is supposed not to be in head normal form) is a head reduction which starts from a term *t* and ends on a head normal form.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] From an abstract point of view, head reduction is the way a program computes when it evaluates a recursive sub-program.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] To understand how such a reduction can be implemented is important.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] One of the aims of the Krivine machine is to propose a process to reduct a term in head normal form and to describe formally this process.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] Like Turing used an abstract machine to describe formally the notion of algorithm, Krivine used an abstract machine to describe formally the notion of head normal form reduction.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] We will see further how the Krivine machine reduces the term ((*λ* 0) (*λ* 0)) (*λ* 0).
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] To implement the head reduction of a term *u v* which is an application, but which is not a redex, one must reduce the body *u* to exhibit an abstraction and therefore create a redex with *v*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] To reduce always the body of an application first is called *call by name*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The Krivine machine implements *call by name*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The presentation of the Krivine machine given here is based on notations of lambda terms that use de Bruijn indices and assumes that the terms of which it computes the head normal forms are closed.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] It modifies the current **state** until it cannot do it anymore, in which case it obtains a head normal form.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] This head normal form represents the result of the computation or yields an error, meaning that the term it started from is not correct.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] However, it can enter an infinite sequence of transitions, which means that the term it attempts reducing has no head normal form and corresponds to a non terminating computation.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] It has been proved that the Krivine machine implements correctly the call by name head normal form reduction in the lambda-calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] Moreover, the Krivine machine is deterministic, since each pattern of the state corresponds to at most one machine transition.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The term is a λ-term with de Bruijn indices.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The stack and the environment belong to the same recursive data structure.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] More precisely, the environment and the stack are lists of pairs *<term, environment>*, that are called *closures*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] In what follows, the insertion as the head of a list ℓ (stack or environment) of an element *a* is written *a:ℓ*, whereas the empty list is written □.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The stack is the location where the machine stores the closures that must be evaluated furthermore, whereas the environment is the association between the indices and the closures at a given time during the evaluation.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The first element of the environment is the closure associated with the index *0*, the second element corresponds to the closure associated with index *1* etc.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] If the machine has to evaluate an index, it fetches there the pair *<term, environment>* the closure that yields the term to be evaluated and the environment in which this term must be evaluated.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] This intuitive explanations allow understanding the operating rules of the machine.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] If one writes *t* for term, p for stack, and e for environment, the states associated with these three entities will be written *t*, p, e.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The rules explain how the machine transforms a state into another state, after identifying the patterns among the states.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The *initial state* aims to evaluate a term *t*, it is the state *t*,□,□, in which the term is *t* and the stack and the environment are empty.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The *final state* (in absence of error) is of the form *λ t*, □, e, in other words, the resulting terms is an abstraction together with its environment and an empty stack.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The transition ***App*** removes the parameter of an application and put it on the stack for further evaluation.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The transition ***Abs*** removes the λ of the term and pop up the closure from the top of the stack and put it on the top of the environment.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] This closure corresponds to the de Bruijn index *0* in the new environment.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The transition ***Zero*** takes the first closure of the environment.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The term of this closure becomes the current term and the environment of this closure becomes the current environment.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The transition ***Succ*** removes the first closure of the environment list and decreases the value of the index.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] Let us evaluate the term (*λ* 0 0) (*λ* 0) which corresponds to the term (*λ* *x*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] The conclusion is that the head normal form of the term (*λ* 0 0) (*λ* 0) is *λ* 0 Putting variables back in: the head normal form of the term (*λ* *x*.
[src:graph-reduction/krivine-machine] This confirms the above fact that the normal form of the term ((*λ* 0) (*λ* 0)) (*λ* 0) is (*λ* 0) Or with variables: ((*λ* *x*.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The **SECD machine** is an influential virtual machine and abstract machine intended as a target for compilers of functional programming languages.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The letters stand for `stack`, `environment`, `control`, `dump`, respectively, which are the internal registers of the machine.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The registers `stack`, `control`, and `dump` point to (some realizations of) stacks, and `environment` points to (some realization of) an associative array.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The machine was the first to be specifically designed to evaluate lambda calculus expressions.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] It was originally described by Peter Landin in "The Mechanical Evaluation of Expressions" in 1964.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The description published by Landin was fairly abstract, and left many implementation choices open (like an operational semantics).
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Lispkit Lisp was a compiler based on the SECD machine, and the SECD machine has been used as the target for other systems such as Lisp/370.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] In 1989, researchers at the University of Calgary worked on a hardware implementation of the machine, with the same rationale as a high-level language computer architecture related to a Lisp machine.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Turner (2012) points out that the ALGOL 60 programming language could not return functions from other functions (rendering functions no longer first-class).
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] A function nested inside another function could refer to a variable living on the outer function's stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the nested function were returned from the outer function, then it would be referring to a variable in a stack frame that is no longer present.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Turner notes that Landin's SECD machine solves this problem (thus allowing functions to return functions), as a function value is now represented with a closure on the heap that can store the environment of variables it should use irrespective of what happens on the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] When evaluation of an expression begins, the expression is loaded as the only element of control **`C`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] During evaluation of **`C`** it is converted to reverse Polish notation (RPN) with `ap` (for apply) being the only operator.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] For example, the expression `F (G X)` (a single list element) is changed to the list `X:G:ap:F:ap`.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Evaluation of **`C`** proceeds similarly to other RPN expressions.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the first item in **`C`** is a value, it is pushed onto the stack **`S`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] More exactly, if the item is an identifier, the value pushed onto the stack will be the binding for that identifier in the current environment **`E`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the item is an abstraction, a closure is constructed to preserve the bindings of its free variables (which are in **`E`**), and it is this closure which is pushed onto the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the item is **`ap`**, two values are popped off the stack and the application done (first applied to second).
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the result of the application is a value, it is pushed onto the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If the application is of an abstraction to a value, however, it will result in a lambda calculus expression that may itself be an application (rather than a value), and so cannot be pushed onto the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Completed evaluation is indicated by **`C`** being empty, in which case the result will be on the stack **`S`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The last saved evaluation state on **`D`** is then popped, and the result of the completed evaluation is pushed onto the stack contents restored from **`D`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Evaluation of the restored state then continues as above.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If **`C`** and **`D`** are both empty, overall evaluation has completed with the result on the stack **`S`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Functions take their arguments from the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The arguments to built-in instructions are encoded immediately after them in the instruction stream.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Like all internal data-structures, the stack is a list, with the **`S`** register pointing at the list's *head* or beginning.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Due to the list structure, the stack need not be a continuous block of memory, so stack space is available as long as there is a single free memory cell.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Even when all cells have been used, garbage collection may yield additional free memory.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Obviously, specific implementations of the SECD structure can implement the stack as a canonical stack structure, thus improving the overall efficiency of the virtual machine, provided that a strict bound be put on the dimension of the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The **`C`** register points at the head of the code or instruction list that will be evaluated.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The current variable environment is managed by the **`E`** register, which points at a list of lists.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Each individual list represents one environment level: the parameters of the current function are in the head of the list, variables that are free in the current function, but bound by a surrounding function, are in other elements of **`E`**.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The dump, at whose head the **`D`** register points, is used as temporary storage for values of the other registers, for example during function calls.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] It can be likened to the return stack of other machines.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The memory organization of the SECD machine is similar to the model used by most functional language interpreters: a number of memory cells, each of which can hold either an *atom* (a simple value, for example *13*), or represent an empty or non-empty list.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] In the latter case, the cell holds two pointers to other cells, one representing the first element, the other representing the list except for the first element.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The two pointers are traditionally named *car* and *cdr* respectively—but the more modern terms *head* and *tail* are often used instead.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The different types of values that a cell can hold are distinguished by a *tag*.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Often different types of atoms (integers, strings, etc.) are distinguished as well.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The memory cells 3 to 5 do not belong to our list, the cells of which can be distributed randomly over the memory.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Cell 2 is the head of the list, it points to cell 1, which holds the first element's value, and the list containing only *2* and *3* (beginning at cell 6).
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] Cell 6 points at a cell holding 2 and at cell 7, which represents the list containing only *3*.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] It does so by pointing at cell 8 containing the value *3*, and pointing at an empty list (*nil*) as cdr.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] In the SECD machine, cell 0 always implicitly represents the empty list, so no special tag value is needed to signal an empty list (everything needing that can simply point to cell 0).
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] The principle that the cdr in a list cell must point at another list is just a convention.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] If both car and cdr point at atoms, that will yield a pair, usually written like `(1 .
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] A number of additional instructions for basic functions like car, cdr, list construction, integer addition, I/O, etc. exist.
[src:graph-reduction/secd-machine] They all take any necessary parameters from the stack.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The **SKI combinator calculus** is a combinatory logic system and a computational system.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] It can be thought of as a computer programming language, though it is not convenient for writing software.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Instead, it is important in the mathematical theory of algorithms because it is an extremely simple Turing complete language.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] It can be likened to a reduced version of the untyped lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] It was introduced by Moses Schönfinkel and Haskell Curry.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] All operations in lambda calculus can be encoded via abstraction elimination into the SKI calculus as binary trees whose leaves are one of the three symbols **S**, **K**, and **I** (called *combinators*).
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Although the most formal representation of the objects in this system requires binary trees, for simpler typesetting they are often represented as parenthesized expressions, as a shorthand for the tree they represent.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Any subtrees may be parenthesized, but often only the right-side subtrees are parenthesized, with left associativity implied for any unparenthesized applications.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Using this notation, a tree whose left subtree is the tree **KS** and whose right subtree is the tree **SK** can be written as **KS**(**SK**).
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] If more explicitness is desired, the implied parentheses can be included as well: ((**KS**)(**SK**)).
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Informally, and using programming language jargon, a tree (*xy*) can be thought of as an application of the function *x* to an argument *y*.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] When evaluated (*i.e.*, when the "function" is "applied" to the argument), the tree "returns a value", *i.e.*, transforms into another tree.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The "function", "argument" and the "value" are either combinators or binary trees with application nodes.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] If they are binary trees, they may be thought of as functions too, if needed.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Example computation: **SKSK** evaluates to **KK**(**SK**) by the **S**-rule.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] As no further rule can be applied, the computation halts here.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] For all trees *x* and all trees *y*, **SK***xy* will always evaluate to *y* in two steps, **K***y*(*xy*) = *y*, so the ultimate result of evaluating **SK***xy* will always be the same as the result of evaluating *y*.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] We say that **SK***x* and **I** are "functionally equivalent" for any *x*, because they always yield the same result when applied to any *y*.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] From these definitions it can be shown that SKI calculus, while being a minimalistic system, can fully perform any computations of the lambda calculus.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] All occurrences of **I** in any expression can be replaced by (**SKK**) or (**SKS**) or (**SK** *x*) for any *x*, and the resulting expression will yield the same result.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] So the "**I**" is merely syntactic sugar.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Since **I** is optional, the system is also referred to as **SK calculus** or **SK combinator calculus**.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] It is possible to define a complete system using only one (improper) combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] It is possible to reconstruct **S**, **K**, and **I** from the iota combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Applying ι to itself gives ιι = ι**SK** = **SSKK** = **SK**(**KK**) which is functionally equivalent to **I**.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] **K** can be constructed by applying ι twice to **I** (which is equivalent to application of ι to itself): ι(ι(ιι)) = ι(ιι**SK**) = ι(**ISK**) = ι(**SK**) = **SKSK** = **K**.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Nothing is a term if not required to be so by the first two rules.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] If Δ is a derivation ending in an expression of the form *α*((**K**β)*γ*)*ι*, then Δ followed by the term *αβι* is a derivation.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] If Δ is a derivation ending in an expression of the form *α*(((**S**β)*γ*)*δ*)*ι*, then Δ followed by the term *α*((*βδ*)(*γδ*))*ι* is a derivation.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Assuming a sequence is a valid derivation to begin with, it can be extended using these rules.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] All derivations of length 1 are valid derivations.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] This is also known as **U** combinator, **U***x* = *xx*.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Or, using the equation **U***x* = *xx* as its definition directly, we immediately get **U** **U** = **U** **U**.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] or it can be seen as defining yet another combinator directly, **H***xy* = *x*(*yy*).
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] This function can be used to achieve recursion.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The term *α* will have to employ some kind of conditional to stop at some "base case" and not make the recursive call then, to avoid divergence.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] which gives us one possible encoding of the **Y** combinator.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] A shorter variation replaces its two leading subterms with just **SSI**, since **H**α(**H**α) = **SHH**α = **SSIH**α.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] And with a pseudo-Haskell syntax it becomes the exceptionally short **Y** = **U** .
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Following this approach, other fixpoint combinator definitions are possible.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The **Z** combinator will work in strict languages (also called eager languages), where the applicative evaluation order is in effect.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Its difference from the **Y** combinator is that it is using $Qx=B(Ux)I=S(K(Ux))I=S(BS(BKU))(KI)x$ as the $\eta$ -expanded form of **Y'**s plain $Ux$ .
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] SKI combinator calculus can also implement Boolean logic in the form of an *if-then-else* structure.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The key is in defining the two Boolean expressions.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] Once true and false are defined, all Boolean logic can be implemented in terms of Booleans acting as *if-then-else* structures.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] This proves that the SKI system can fully express Boolean logic.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] The axioms **AK** and **AS**, and the rule **MP** are complete for the implicational fragment of intuitionistic logic.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] This connection between the types of combinators and the corresponding logical axioms is an instance of the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] There usually are multiple ways to do a reduction.
[src:graph-reduction/ski-combinator-calculus] If the term has a normal form, it is unique, hence the same result will be reached in such a case whatever the order of operations.
